"the host address (**HostID**) by performing a bitwise logical AND between "
"the IP address and the complement of the mask."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:65
msgid ""
"There are also specific addresses within a network, which must be "
"identified. The first address of a range as well as the last one have a "
"particular role:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:67
msgid ""
"The first address of a range is the **network address**. It is used to "
"identify networks and to route information from one network to another."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:69
msgid ""
"The last address of a range is the **broadcast address**. It is used to "
"broadcast information to all the machines on the network."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "MAC address / IP address"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:74
msgid ""
"A **MAC address** is a physical identifier written in the factory onto the "
"device. This is sometimes referred to as the hardware address. It consists "
"of 6 bytes often given in hexadecimal form (for example 5E:FF:56:A2:AF:15).  "
"It is composed of: 3 bytes of the manufacturer identifier and 3 bytes of the "
"serial number."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:76
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:388
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:637
msgid "!!! Warning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This last statement is nowadays a little less true with virtualization. There are also software solutions for changing the MAC address.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:81
msgid ""
"An Internet Protocol (**IP**) address is an identification number "
"permanently or temporarily assigned to each device connected to a computer "
"network using the Internet Protocol.  One part defines the network address "
"(NetID or SubnetID as the case may be), the other part defines the address "
"of the host in the network (HostID). The relative size of each part varies "
"according to the network (sub)mask."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:83
msgid ""
"An IPv4 address defines an address on 4 bytes. The number of available "
"addresses being close to saturation a new standard was created, the IPv6 "
"defined on 16 bytes."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:85
msgid ""
"IPv6 is often represented by 8 groups of 2 bytes separated by a colon. "
"Insignificant zeros can be omitted, one or more groups of 4 consecutive "
"zeros can be replaced by a double colon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:87
msgid ""
"Subnet masks have from 0 to 128 bits. (for example "
"21ac:0000:0000:0611:21e0:00ba:321b:54da/64 or 21ac::611:21e0:ba:321b:54da/64)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:89
msgid ""
"In a web address or URL (Uniform Resource Locator), an ip address can be "
"followed by a colon and the port address (which indicates the application to "
"which the data is destined). Also to avoid confusion in a URL, the IPv6 "
"address is written in square brackets [ ], colon, port address."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:91
msgid "IP and MAC addresses must be unique on a network!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "DNS Domain"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:95
msgid ""
"Client machines can be part of a DNS (**Domain Name System**, e.g., "
"`mydomain.lan`) domain."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:97
msgid ""
"The fully qualified machine name (**FQDN**) becomes `pc-rocky.mydomain.lan`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:99
msgid ""
"A set of computers can be grouped into a logical, name-resolving, set called "
"a DNS domain. A DNS domain is not, of course, limited to a single physical "
"network."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:101
msgid ""
"In order for a computer to be part of a DNS domain, it must be given a DNS "
"suffix (here `mydomain.lan`) as well as servers that it can query."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:102
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reminder of the OSI model"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:105
msgid "!!! Note \"Memory aid\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "    To remember the order of the layers of the OSI model, remember the following sentence: __Please Do Not Touch Steven's Pet Alligator__.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"|  Layer            |  Protocoles                                  |\n"
"|-------------------|----------------------------------------------|\n"
"|  7 - Application  |  POP, IMAP, SMTP, SSH, SNMP, HTTP, FTP, ...  |\n"
"|  6 - Presentation |  ASCII, MIME, ...                            |\n"
"|  5 - Session      |  TLS, SSL, NetBIOS, ...                      |\n"
"|  4 - Transport    |  TLS, SSL, TCP, UDP, ...                     |\n"
"|  3 - Network      |  IPv4, IPv6, ARP, ...                        |\n"
"|  2 - Data Link    |  Ethernet, WiFi, Token Ring, ...             |\n"
"|  1 - Physical     |  Cables, optical fibers, radio waves, ...    |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Layer 1** (Physical) supports transmission over a communication channel (Wifi, Optical fiber, RJ cable, etc.).\n"
"Unit: the bit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:124
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Layer 2** (Data Link) supports network topology\n"
"(token-ring, star, bus, etc.), data splitting and transmission errors.\n"
"Unit: the frame.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Layer 3** (Network) supports end-to-end data transmission (IP routing = Gateway).\n"
"Unit: the packet.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:131
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Layer 4** (Transport) supports service type (connected or unconnected)\n"
"encryption and flow control.\n"
"Unit: the segment or the datagram.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:133
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Layer 5** (Session) supports the communication between two computers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:135
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Layer 6** (Presentation) represents the area that is independent of data at the application layer. Essentially this layer translates from network format to the application format, or from the application format to the network format.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:139
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Layer 7** (Application) represents the contact with the user.\n"
"It provides the services offered by the network: http, dns, ftp, imap,\n"
"pop, smtp, etc.\n"
msgstr ""

